      "content": "# Past Lives\n\n## Logline\nNORA measures the life she chose against the childhood self and first love she left behind, turning in-yun (destiny/fate) into a quiet question of timing, language, and home.\n\n## Taglines\n- Some lives continue without you.\n- What if timing is the whole story?\n- Every goodbye keeps another self alive.\n\n## Synopsis\nPast Lives opens with Nora looks up and stares directly at the camera. The film then moves between childhood, screens, marriage, and New York public spaces, letting ordinary locations carry the weight of lives that almost happened. NORA is not chasing spectacle; she is measuring distance, memory, and identity against the person who remembers who she used to be. Scene 16 gives the deck an early production anchor: Nora breaking down and crying in Arthur's arms after Hae Sung's Uber drives away . The final movement lands on Scene 16: Nora breaking down and crying in Arthur's arms after Hae Sung's Uber drives away .\n\n## Film Identity\n- **Genre:** Drama / Romance\n- **Period:** Late-90s, 12 years later, and 12 years after that (Contemporary)\n- **Tone:** Melancholic romantic drama\n- **Core engine:** Evolves from a competitive, crying child in Seoul into a grounded, ambitious playwright in New York who ultimately makes peace with the life she chose over the life she left behind.\n- **Production read:** 5 major locations, 16 scenes, and a craft burden centered on performance, language, time jumps, restrained blocking, and precise urban atmosphere.\n\n## Themes\n**In-Yun (Destiny/Fate)**\nScene 9 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Arthur leaning across the table and kissing Nora deeply after discussing In-Yun.\n\n**Immigration, Identity, and the lives left behind**\nScene 16 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Nora breaking down and crying in Arthur's arms after Hae Sung's Uber drives away .\n\n**Childhood vs. Adulthood**\nScene 2 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Hae Sung wipes Na Young's wet face with his sleeves after she cries about placing second in exams.\n\n**Acceptance of the present**\nScene 13 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Hae Sung looking at photos of Nora's wedding on her phone while the massive city looms over them .\n\n## Scope / Production Read\n- **Scenes:** 16\n- **Locations:** 5\n- **Exterior Scenes:** 8\n- **Night / Continuous Scenes:** 5\n- **VFX / Stunt Scenes:** 1\n- **Hero Props:** 4\n- **Hero prop focus:** basketball, laptop\n- **Complexity:** Medium scope. Emotionally precise scope. The deck should foreground performance, language, time jumps, cities, screens, and quiet blocking rather than spectacle.",
